constructing the base-pair by starting with the bases in their ideal pairing relationship and then moving them into their actual positions. This motion can be accomplished either by first rotating the bases about their pivot points and then translating them into the final positions, or by first translating them and then rotating them about their pivot points. The same equations are obtained in both cases. For convenience, we shall start with the second case and then consider the first.

While the translation of the bases can be treated as a single operation, the rotations of the bases about their pivot points will be considered in 3 steps in order to derive the appropriate matrix equations. The reason is that, when the coordinates of an atom are multiplied by a rotation matrix, as in equations {}) and (3), the rotation takes place about the origin of the frame in which the coordinates are measured. Thus, to derive the matrix equations, we must first move the origins of the base coordinate frames to their pivot points, perform the rotations, and then move the origins back to their original positions relative to the rotated base atoms. To express the motion mathematically, let:

P, = coordinates of a given atom measured in the

base-pair coordinate frame;

P., P2, = coordinates of the atom as seen in the 2 base frames after initial translation;

Pi, Pz, = coordinates after moving the base origins to the pivot points;

Pi,: Pz, = coordinates after rotating about the pivot points;

P;, Px = final coordinates of the atom after moving the origins back into position.
